title: For Sale/Trade:  S&W 18-1 K-frame .22 LR Combat Masterpiece 4"
postcontent:
Made a trade that included this Smith & Wesson & it's WAY too nice for me to beat up.  All original with correct box, onion skin, & some papers.  Serial # checks to be 1961.  Beautiful, tight, perfect timing & lock-up.  These were only made for a couple of years (late 1959-early 1961) & then changed to the 18-2 & later were the -3 & -4.  Has double pins & 3 screws & recessed cylinders..  Very little info available on these.  All parts match including the grips.  The screws aren't buggered & all lines & seams match perfectly.  

This is a very rare gun to find in this condition.  The 18-1 is harder to find than a Colt Diamondback 22 & worth much more with the correct factory box.  This isn't a crappy ebay remake, it's the real deal with ball-point pen markings that are almost illegible.  The only trades that would interest me would be a H&R 999 4" Sportsman or a Ruger Single-six 4 5/8" plus considerable cash.

I'll listen to offers.  Save the lowball ones.  If your offer doesn't have at least 4 digits to the left of the decimal point, no thanks. The 18-2, -3, -4 & 17s are bringing $6-800 for just the gun.  Face to face, cash or whatever trade we work out & you travel to me.  NO SHIPPING OR LONG DISTANCE SALES. REDACTED

title: For Sale:  Mosin Nagant w/Hex Receivers -- Only $425 for both!!
postcontent:
Model 1891/30 (Ð²Ð¸Ð½ÑÐ¾Ð²ÐºÐ° Ð¾Ð±ÑÐ°Ð·ÑÐ° 1891/30-Ð³Ð¾ Ð³Ð¾Ð´Ð°, Ð²Ð¸Ð½ÑÐ¾Ð²ÐºÐ° ÐÐ¾ÑÐ¸Ð½Ð°): The most prolific version of the MosinâNagant. It was produced for standard issue to all Soviet infantry from 1930 to 1945. Most Dragoon rifles were also converted to the M1891/30 standard. It was commonly used as a sniper rifle in World War II. Early sniper versions had a 4x PE or PEM scope, a Soviet-made copy of a Zeiss design, while later rifles used smaller, simpler, and easier-to-produce 3.5x PU scopes. Because the scope was mounted above the chamber, the bolt handle was replaced with a longer, bent version on sniper rifles so the shooter could work the bolt without the scope interfering with it. Its design was based on the Dragoon rifle with the following modifications:
--Flat rear sights and restamping of sights in metres, instead of arshinii.
--A cylindrical receiver, replacing the octagonal (commonly called "hex") receiver. Early production 91/30s (from 1930 to 1936) and converted Dragoon rifles retained the octagonal receiver. These rifles are less common and regarded as generally more desirable by collectors.
--A hooded post front sight, replacing the blade on previous weapons.[13]

The vest is meant to be worn on the outside of clothing and has large velcro pads to place various patches or one large patch that states the business, organization or agency. It has several pockets conveniently located so you can store extra magazines, possibly a first aid kit, a small survival kit, food or other tactical equipment.

This vest is designed to resist most pistol calibers. This vest will have no effect on any rifle calibers or stabbing. Level III-A vests are the highest protection against pistols.

If you have any questions, please feel free to TEXT (no calls because of my odd work hours/days) REDACTED or email!

Here is some additional information regarding bulletproof vests: 

"When a handgun bullet strikes body armor, it is caught in a "web" of very strong fibers. These fibers absorb and disperse the impact energy that is transmitted to the vest from the bullet, causing the bullet to deform or "mushroom". Â Additional energy is absorbed by each successive layer of material in the vest, until such time as the bullet has been stopped."

It is important to know that Level II-A, II and III-A all stop the overwhelming majority of pistol projectiles you are ever likely to encounter (plus 12 gauge, OO buckshot), and also to know that NO armor is ever 100% 'bulletproof' under ALL conceivable circumstances.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1885 Torino Rifle
postcontent:
My great grandfather fought in world war 1 and world war 2 and been in family every since and now it sits here collecting dust and looking for a new home for it....and in need a working firearm....heres sum information about it i have found: The Vetterli rifles were a series of Swiss army service rifles in use from 1869 to circa 1890, when they were replaced with Schmidt-Rubin rifles. Modified Vetterli rifles were also used by the Italian Army.
The Swiss Vetterli rifles combined the American Winchester Model 1866's tubular magazine and a bolt system derived from the German Dreyse needle gun. They were also the first repeating rifle to feature a self-cocking action and a small caliber. Due to the Swiss Federal Council's early 1866 decision to equip the army with a breechloading repeating rifle, the Vetterli rifles were, at the time of their introduction, the most advanced military rifles in Europe. The Vetterli was the replacement for Milbank-Amsler rifles, which were a metallic cartridge conversion from previous muzzle loading rifles.

Overall this is a very nice revolver from the pre-MIM Smith & Wesson era.

The walnut grips are on it right now, and a rubber Hogue monogrip will be included as well as one HKS speedloader. Price is $580; $20 less without the walnut grips. I'm not looking to make any trades, so if you do want to trade something, it would have to be very interesting.
